messages.text:
Just to clear up some of the confusion overnight üòÇ..

Obviously I get the point here about <theoretical> infinite Angels. We workshopped it to death. I think people are way overestimating how many will take the 50k deal. And way underestimating how conservative and long term our treasury vault plans are.

Another way to look at it is like a multi year lock up.  But at the end, users don't all get to dump the tokens. Instead we manage them carefully.

Let's say in a few years from now, we hire the CZ and Vitalik as office assistants. We may give them 5% of their wage in YLD with a vesting period to incentivise performance. 

Until they decide to sell some YLD (and historically staff are the most diamond hands of all), we are talking like a drip feed around 2028. I think it's fair to assume that's long than most newcommers will hodl.

If we have a problem of too many Diamond tier users by 2028, you guys can fly your private jets to Dubai and we can all sit down and review it.

Finally, the offer for lifetime Angel at 50k isn't guaranteed to always be there. I think everyone sees how great of an oportunity we have here to grow, and let the market see the strengths of our team applied in a new and relevant way that is hugely in demand.  Let's all just take a moment to appreciate that we are talking about the problem of TOO MANY Diamonds üòÇ. A welcome conversation after 2 years of bear market.

that is displayed before the program is allowed to run at all, which specifically states

text.text: "This file has the extension .exe. It may harm the computer."

text:
wherein the user is told if they are certain they wish to run the program, followed by an option to either allow or prevent the computer from executing the unknown exe.

The other point I made is that Lucas is entirely kept isolated from the demands of the community to raise rates, there's no pressure on his team to raise or lower rates, it's never a marketing move. If you wish to get a 1k allocation, you pledge 1k.

Quite a few advantages I would say. :-)

messages.text:
I'm sorry if I wasn't clear enough my numbers were just an example, let's make another one.

If you pledge 200 and your allocation ends up being 150 the other 50 are returned to your wallet. From that allocation you received of 150, 10% comes off as the fee.

We don't take the fee of your pledge amount, the fee is taken from the allocation you receive.

This way the 50 returned to your account are not accounted towards the fee, only the amount that is allocated to you, which in my example was 150.
